      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/software-quality-assurance",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "SQA: Version-controlled, documented FEA code with regression test suite",
        "description": "The FEA solver must be under version control with a documented release history; a regression test suite covering at least five canonical benchmark problems must pass; solver validation documentation must be available for regulatory review. Ansys Mechanical 2022R2 and FDA in-house FEA code both satisfy these criteria."
      },
      "rationale": "All three FEA implementations (FDA in-house, Ansys Mechanical 2022R2, DePuy Synthes internal solver) operate under formal software quality management systems. FDA code is maintained under 21 CFR Part 11-compliant version control with full audit trail. Ansys Mechanical is a commercially validated solver with ISO 9001 certification and published V&V documentation. DePuy Synthes solver follows IEC 62304 software lifecycle processes. Regression benchmarks against ASME V&V 10 test problems confirm solver correctness. Achieved Gradation 3 exceeds the required Gradation 2 for a Model Risk Level 3 device."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/numerical-code-verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/numerical-code-verification",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Code verification: Manufactured solution or benchmark comparison with documented error norms",
        "description": "Solver must demonstrate correct implementation of governing equations via method-of-manufactured-solutions (MMS) or comparison to published analytical/benchmark solutions for at least two relevant problem classes (linear elasticity, contact). Observed order of convergence must be within 10% of theoretical order."
      },
      "rationale": "Code verification was performed for all three solvers using the method of manufactured solutions for linear-elastic beam bending and Hertzian contact. Observed convergence rates matched theoretical second-order accuracy to within 7%. Additionally, each solver was benchmarked against the NAFEMS LE1 and LE10 linear elasticity test cases, achieving errors below 0.5%. The FDA in-house code was further verified against the ASME V&V 10.1 annex benchmark suite. Achieved Gradation 2 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/discretization-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/discretization-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Discretization error: GCI < 2% on all QoIs; mesh convergence study documented across ≥3 refinement levels",
        "description": "A formal mesh convergence study using the Grid Convergence Index (GCI) method per Roache (1998) must be performed across at least three systematically refined mesh densities. GCI on stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm must each be below 2%. The converged mesh must be used for all validation simulations."
      },
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the non-cannulated pedicle screw construct model with mesh densities of approximately 45 k, 180 k, and 720 k elements (refinement ratio r = 2). GCI values: stiffness 0.8%, yield force 1.2%, force at 40 mm 1.6% — all below the 2% acceptance criterion. The apparent order of convergence p = 1.94 is consistent with second-order hexahedral elements. The 180 k element mesh was selected for production runs, balancing accuracy and computational cost. Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/numerical-solver-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Solver error: Iterative convergence tolerance ≤ 1e-6 on force residual; energy balance error < 0.1%",
        "description": "Nonlinear solver must achieve force residual norm below 1×10⁻⁶ at each load step. Energy balance error across the full loading history must remain below 0.1%. Contact penetration must be below 0.001 mm at all interfaces."
      },
      "rationale": "All three FEA implementations used Newton-Raphson iteration with force residual convergence tolerance of 1×10⁻⁷ (tighter than required). Energy balance errors were monitored throughout the 40 mm displacement ramp and remained below 0.05% in all runs. Maximum contact penetration at screw-rod and screw-block interfaces was 0.0003 mm, well within the acceptance criterion. Solver log files are archived in the model repository. Achieved Gradation 2 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/use-error",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Use error: Independent analyst review of model setup; documented simulation protocol",
        "description": "A documented simulation protocol (boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, load application) must exist. An analyst independent of the original model builder must reproduce the nominal result within 1% before validation runs are accepted."
      },
      "rationale": "A formal simulation protocol document was prepared by the primary analyst and independently reviewed by a second analyst at FDA OSEL. The independent analyst reproduced the nominal stiffness result within 0.4% using the archived model files and protocol. Material property assignments, boundary conditions (fixed base, displacement-controlled loading block), and contact pair definitions were verified against the protocol checklist. No discrepancies were found. The protocol is version-controlled and linked to the model archive. Achieved Gradation 2 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-form",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model form: Justified constitutive models with literature support; sensitivity to model form documented",
        "description": "The choice of constitutive model (e.g., bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V, linear elastic for CoCr rod) must be justified with reference to published material characterization data. A model-form sensitivity study varying the constitutive law (e.g., Ramberg-Osgood vs. bilinear) must show QoI sensitivity below 5%."
      },
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V pedicle screws were modeled with bilinear isotropic hardening (E = 114 GPa, σ_y = 880 MPa, E_t = 1.2 GPa) based on ASTM F136 coupon data from three material lots. CoCr rod was modeled as linear elastic (E = 210 GPa) consistent with the sub-yield loading regime confirmed by strain gauge measurements. UHMWPE vertebral body blocks were modeled as linear elastic (E = 1.1 GPa, ν = 0.46) following published indentation data. Model-form sensitivity study comparing bilinear hardening vs. Ramberg-Osgood (n=12) showed stiffness difference of 0.9%, yield force difference of 2.3%, force-at-40mm difference of 3.1% — all below the 5% threshold. Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/model-inputs",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Model inputs: Traceable material and geometry inputs with documented uncertainty bounds",
        "description": "All model input parameters (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) must be traceable to measurement data or published standards. Uncertainty bounds must be documented for each input. A variance-based sensitivity analysis must identify the top three contributors to QoI uncertainty."
      },
      "rationale": "Screw geometry was digitized from CMM measurements of three production screws (mean ± 1σ reported for all critical dimensions: outer diameter 7.50 ± 0.02 mm, thread pitch 2.75 ± 0.01 mm, core diameter 4.85 ± 0.03 mm). Material properties were sourced from lot-specific tensile coupon testing (n=5 per lot, three lots). Boundary condition uncertainties (insertion torque ±0.2 N·m, block stiffness ±5%) were propagated through a Monte Carlo analysis (n=1000 samples). Variance decomposition identified Ti-6Al-4V yield strength (38%), UHMWPE elastic modulus (27%), and screw core diameter (19%) as the dominant uncertainty contributors. Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-samples",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test samples: Production-representative specimens with documented traceability; N ≥ 10",
        "description": "Test specimens must be manufactured from production-representative material lots with full dimensional inspection and material certification. Minimum sample size N=10 across at least two independent test batches. Coefficient of variation on stiffness must be reported."
      },
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were assembled from three production lots (FDA warehouse stock, DePuy Synthes production release). Full dimensional inspection confirmed all screws within drawing tolerances. Material certifications (mill certificates, tensile coupons) were obtained for each lot. Six constructs were tested at Laboratory 1 (FDA OSEL biomechanics lab) and five at Laboratory 2 (DePuy Synthes internal test facility). Inter-laboratory coefficient of variation on stiffness was 5.3%, consistent with expected inter-lab variability for this test type. N=11 exceeds the minimum of 10. Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/test-conditions",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Test conditions: Multiple loading rates and environmental conditions; calibrated instrumentation",
        "description": "Testing must be conducted at a minimum of two loading rates to assess rate sensitivity. Load cell and displacement transducer calibration must be traceable to NIST standards. Environmental conditions (temperature, humidity) must be monitored and reported. Ideally, wet/dry conditions should be compared."
      },
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted at a single loading rate of 2 mm/min per ASTM F1717 protocol. While calibration traceability to NIST standards was confirmed for all instrumentation at both laboratories, only one loading rate was evaluated. A literature review (Goel et al., 2006; Niinomi, 2008) indicates that Ti-6Al-4V pedicle screw constructs exhibit minimal rate sensitivity below 10 mm/min under quasi-static conditions, providing qualitative justification for the single-rate approach. However, this was not experimentally confirmed in the current study. Achieved Gradation 2 is below the required Gradation 3; this shortfall is addressed in the decision record offset rationale."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/equivalency-of-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/equivalency-of-input-parameters",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Equivalency: FEA inputs matched to measured experimental parameters within documented tolerances",
        "description": "FEA model inputs (geometry, material properties, boundary conditions) must be matched to the as-tested experimental parameters, not nominal design values. Documented matching tolerances: geometry within 0.05 mm, material properties within 5% of measured lot values, insertion torque within 0.5 N·m of measured value."
      },
      "rationale": "FEA models were updated to reflect as-measured specimen geometry (CMM data per specimen), as-tested material properties (lot-specific tensile coupon data), and as-measured insertion torques (torque wrench data recorded for each construct assembly). Geometry matching was within 0.02 mm for all critical dimensions. Material property matching was within 2.1% for elastic modulus and 3.4% for yield strength. Insertion torque matching was within 0.15 N·m. This per-specimen model updating approach ensures that the validation comparison reflects genuine predictive capability rather than tuning to nominal values. Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/output-comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/output-comparison",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Output comparison: Quantitative validation metric E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs; percentage difference < 10%",
        "description": "The validation comparison must use a quantitative metric that accounts for both model prediction uncertainty and experimental measurement uncertainty. The ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval must be below 1.96 (95% confidence threshold) for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm). Additionally, percentage difference between FEA mean and experimental mean must be below 10% for each QoI."
      },
      "rationale": "Quantitative validation metrics were computed for all three QoIs across both laboratories. Stiffness: E/uval = 0.87 (Lab 1), 1.12 (Lab 2); percentage differences 1.3% and 3.0% respectively. Yield force: E/uval = 0.63 (pooled); percentage difference 1.2%. Force at 40 mm: E/uval = 1.44 (pooled); percentage difference 1.96%. All E/uval values are below the 1.96 threshold and all percentage differences are below 10%. Force-at-displacement curves were also compared graphically, showing excellent agreement in the elastic regime and acceptable agreement post-yield. The ensemble spread across three solver implementations (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) was within ±2% for all QoIs, providing additional confidence. Achieved Gradation 4 exceeds the required Gradation 3."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/relevance-of-qoi",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/relevance-of-qoi",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "QoI relevance: QoIs directly linked to clinical failure modes and regulatory submission requirements",
        "description": "The selected QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) must be demonstrably linked to the clinical failure modes of interest (construct loosening, screw fracture) and must be the same metrics required by the applicable regulatory standard (ASTM F1717). A documented traceability matrix from QoI to failure mode to regulatory requirement must be present."
      },
      "rationale": "A formal QoI traceability matrix was developed linking each QoI to clinical failure modes and regulatory requirements. Construct stiffness is the primary indicator of immediate post-operative stability and is directly correlated with construct loosening risk in the literature (Goel et al., 2006). Yield force defines the onset of permanent deformation, which is the precursor to fatigue-driven screw fracture. Force at 40 mm displacement is the specific metric required by ASTM F1717 Section 9.2 for regulatory submissions and characterizes post-yield energy absorption. All three QoIs are explicitly required in ASTM F1717 and are cited in FDA guidance documents for spinal fixation device 510(k) submissions. Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/relevance-of-validation-activities",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "acceptanceCriteria": {
        "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/ac/relevance-of-validation-activities",
        "type": "AcceptanceCriteria",
        "name": "Validation relevance: Validation scenario matches COU geometry, loading, and material within documented similarity bounds",
        "description": "The validation scenario (ASTM F1717 bench test) must match the COU (non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending prediction) in terms of geometry (same screw design, same construct configuration), loading (quasi-static compression-bending), and material (same alloy, same lot). A documented similarity assessment must confirm that the validation scenario is representative of the COU."
      },
      "rationale": "A formal similarity assessment was conducted comparing the validation scenario to the COU. Geometry: validation specimens are the same non-cannulated 7.5 mm screw design from the same production lots as the COU; construct configuration (L4-L5 equivalent, 40 mm span, 5.5 mm CoCr rod) is identical. Loading: ASTM F1717 compression-bending is the direct regulatory test for the COU; loading rate (2 mm/min) is within the quasi-static regime applicable to the COU. Material: same Ti-6Al-4V alloy and CoCr rod as specified in the device design history file. The validation activity is therefore directly representative of the COU with no extrapolation required. Achieved Gradation 3 meets the required level."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-accepted-20260419",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/fda-osel-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 ASME V&V 40 factors for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending FEA model. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved levels at or above the required level for a Model Risk Level 3, Class II device. The single shortfall factor (Test conditions, achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) is addressed in the offset rationale below. Quantitative validation metrics (E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs, percentage differences < 10%) demonstrate that the FEA ensemble reliably predicts ASTM F1717 compression-bending behavior. The three-solver ensemble approach provides additional confidence through independent corroboration. Sensitivity analysis confirmed that model predictions are robust to ±10% variation in dominant input parameters. The overall evidence package is sufficient to support the claim that the FEA modeling framework is credible for predicting compression-bending performance of the non-cannulated pedicle screw construct within the documented operating envelope.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "hasOffsetRationale": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/offset/test-conditions-shortfall",
      "type": "OffsetRationale",
      "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-conditions",
      "justification": "The Test conditions factor achieved Gradation 2 rather than the required Gradation 3 because testing was conducted at a single loading rate (2 mm/min) without experimental confirmation of rate insensitivity. This shortfall is offset by: (1) a comprehensive literature review (Goel et al., 2006; Niinomi, 2008; Hallab et al., 2003) demonstrating that Ti-6Al-4V pedicle screw constructs exhibit negligible rate sensitivity below 10 mm/min under quasi-static conditions, consistent with viscoelastic theory for metallic implants; (2) the ASTM F1717 standard itself specifying a single loading rate of 1–5 mm/min, implying regulatory acceptance of single-rate testing for this device type; (3) the strong performance of all other 12 factors, particularly the high-confidence quantitative output comparison (E/uval < 1.96 for all QoIs) which provides direct empirical evidence of model adequacy under the tested conditions; and (4) the conservative nature of the acceptance decision — the model is used only for the specific loading conditions tested, not for extrapolation to dynamic or fatigue loading regimes. The assessment team judges that this offset evidence is sufficient to accept the credibility of the model for the stated COU despite the single-factor shortfall."
    }
  },
